"use strict";(self.webpackChunksite=self.webpackChunksite||[]).push([["3481"],{74801(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"/2026/05/22/til-stream-tolist-vs-collectors-tolist","metadata":{"permalink":"/knowledgebase/blog/2026/05/22/til-stream-tolist-vs-collectors-tolist","editUrl":"https://github.com/CeyCode/knowledgebase/tree/main/blog/2026-05-22-til-stream-tolist-vs-collectors-tolist.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-22-til-stream-tolist-vs-collectors-tolist.md","title":"TIL: Stream.toList() vs Collectors.toList() in Java","description":"Java 16 added Stream.toList() \u2014 but it\'s not a drop-in replacement for Collectors.toList().","date":"2026-05-22T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"TIL","permalink":"/knowledgebase/blog/tags/til"},{"inline":false,"label":"Java","permalink":"/knowledgebase/blog/tags/java"},{"inline":false,"label":"Streams","permalink":"/knowledgebase/blog/tags/streams"}],"readingTime":1.07,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Kavinda Dewmith","title":"Software Engineer","url":"https://github.com/kavinda","page":{"permalink":"/knowledgebase/blog/authors/kavinda"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/kavinda.png","key":"kavinda"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"TIL: Stream.toList() vs Collectors.toList() in Java","description":"Java 16 added Stream.toList() \u2014 but it\'s not a drop-in replacement for Collectors.toList().","date":"2026-05-22T00:00:00.000Z","authors":["kavinda"],"tags":["til","java","streams"]},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Shrink your Docker images with multi-stage builds","permalink":"/knowledgebase/blog/2026/05/20/docker-multi-stage-builds"}},"content":"Java 16 introduced `Stream.toList()` as a shorter way to collect a stream into a list. Looks like a simple convenience method \u2014 turns out there\'s a meaningful difference.\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## Context\\n\\nI was simplifying some stream pipelines and swapped `collect(Collectors.toList())` for the newer `Stream.toList()`. Tests started failing with `UnsupportedOperationException`. Not obvious why at first.\\n\\n## The discovery\\n\\n`Stream.toList()` returns an **unmodifiable** list. `Collectors.toList()` returns a regular mutable `ArrayList`.\\n\\n```java\\n// Collectors.toList() \u2014 mutable, you can add/remove after\\nList<String> mutable = stream.collect(Collectors.toList());\\nmutable.add(\\"extra\\"); // fine\\n\\n// Stream.toList() \u2014 unmodifiable\\nList<String> immutable = stream.toList();\\nimmutable.add(\\"extra\\"); // throws UnsupportedOperationException\\n```\\n\\n`Collectors.toUnmodifiableList()` existed before Java 16 and gives the same behaviour as `Stream.toList()` \u2014 so the new method is really a shorthand for the unmodifiable version, not the mutable one.\\n\\n## Why it matters\\n\\nIf you\'re collecting into a list you then mutate (sorting in place, removing elements, etc.), the new shorthand will break. The fix is straightforward \u2014 use `Collectors.toList()` when you need mutability, `Stream.toList()` when you don\'t \u2014 but the failure mode is a runtime exception, not a compile error.\\n\\n**Prefer `Stream.toList()` by default** (immutability is usually the right default), and reach for `Collectors.toList()` only when you need to mutate the result.\\n\\n## Source\\n\\n- [JDK-8180352](https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8180352) \u2014 the JEP that introduced `Stream.toList()`\\n- [Java 16 release notes](https://openjdk.org/projects/jdk/16/)"},{"id":"/2026/05/20/docker-multi-stage-builds","metadata":{"permalink":"/knowledgebase/blog/2026/05/20/docker-multi-stage-builds","editUrl":"https://github.com/CeyCode/knowledgebase/tree/main/blog/2026-05-20-docker-multi-stage-builds.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-20-docker-multi-stage-builds.md","title":"Shrink your Docker images with multi-stage builds","description":"Multi-stage builds let you compile inside Docker and ship only what the app actually needs \u2014 no build tools in production.","date":"2026-05-20T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"Tutorial","permalink":"/knowledgebase/blog/tags/tutorial"},{"inline":false,"label":"Docker","permalink":"/knowledgebase/blog/tags/docker"},{"inline":false,"label":"Containers","permalink":"/knowledgebase/blog/tags/containers"}],"readingTime":1.26,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Ceycode Engineering","title":"Shared team account","url":"https://github.com/ceycode","imageURL":"https://github.com/ceycode.png","key":"ceycode-team","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Shrink your Docker images with multi-stage builds","description":"Multi-stage builds let you compile inside Docker and ship only what the app actually needs \u2014 no build tools in production.","date":"2026-05-20T00:00:00.000Z","authors":["ceycode-team"],"tags":["tutorial","docker","containers"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"TIL: Stream.toList() vs Collectors.toList() in Java","permalink":"/knowledgebase/blog/2026/05/22/til-stream-tolist-vs-collectors-tolist"}},"content":"Build tools, test dependencies, and intermediate artifacts have no business being in your production image. Multi-stage builds solve this cleanly.\\n\\n{/* truncate */}\\n\\n## The problem with single-stage builds\\n\\nA naive Dockerfile that installs Maven, compiles a Spring Boot app, and runs it ends up with Maven, the JDK, and all your source code in the final image \u2014 easily 600\u2013800 MB.\\n\\n```dockerfile\\n# single-stage \u2014 too much in the final image\\nFROM eclipse-temurin:21\\nWORKDIR /app\\nCOPY . .\\nRUN ./mvnw package -DskipTests\\nCMD [\\"java\\", \\"-jar\\", \\"target/app.jar\\"]\\n```\\n\\n## Multi-stage: build in one image, run from another\\n\\n```dockerfile\\n# Stage 1: compile\\nFROM eclipse-temurin:21 AS build\\nWORKDIR /app\\nCOPY pom.xml .\\nCOPY src ./src\\nRUN ./mvnw package -DskipTests\\n\\n# Stage 2: run \u2014 just the JRE and the jar\\nFROM eclipse-temurin:21-jre AS runtime\\nWORKDIR /app\\nCOPY --from=build /app/target/app.jar app.jar\\nEXPOSE 8080\\nENTRYPOINT [\\"java\\", \\"-jar\\", \\"app.jar\\"]\\n```\\n\\nThe `--from=build` instruction copies only what you explicitly ask for from the build stage. Docker discards everything else.\\n\\n## Result\\n\\n| Approach | Image size |\\n|---|---|\\n| Single-stage (JDK + Maven + source) | ~750 MB |\\n| Multi-stage (JRE only) | ~230 MB |\\n\\nSmaller image = faster pulls, smaller attack surface, less to scan for vulnerabilities.\\n\\n## Tips\\n\\n- Name your stages (`AS build`, `AS runtime`) so `--from=` is readable\\n- Cache the dependency download layer separately by copying `pom.xml` before `src/` \u2014 Maven will skip re-downloading if `pom.xml` hasn\'t changed\\n- Use a distroless or Alpine JRE for even smaller images\\n\\n---\\n\\n*Have a Docker tip? [Write a TIL or article](/contributing) and share it with the team.*"}]}}')}}]);